    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-11-28T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-11-28T07:00:00-05:00" n="218"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d218">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">841.731/2103: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Special Representative</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HCEM1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">House</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-11-28T12:00:00+00:00"
                            >November 28, 1918—12 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 28—9:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>195. Secret for the President. Referring to our 137 and 146.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d218fn2">Both printed <hi rend="italic">supra.</hi>
                    </note> I am advised through <persName corresp="#p_WSW1">Wiseman</persName> that
                    the British Government have <pb facs="0284" n="214" xml:id="pg_214"/> abolished
                    the political censorship of press despatches for the United States from Great
                    Britain.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HCEM1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Edward House</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
